      "text": "Alex is thirteen and has a history paper due tomorrow. The question, written at the top of an empty page, is: '*When did the modern world begin?*'\n\nThe school library is almost empty. Alex has six textbooks open: Elizabeth I, the Spanish Empire, the Thirty Years' War, the Enlightenment, the Industrial Revolution, World War I. Four hundred years of history. One essay question. No thesis.\n\nAlex's head drops.\n\nWhen it rises, the library is gone. Alex is standing in a torchlit corridor lined with portraits -- kings and queens, generals and philosophers, revolutionaries and tyrants. Each portrait is a doorway.\n\nA voice from nowhere says: '*The modern world did not begin once. It began several times, in several places, for several reasons. You will not find a single answer. You will find a question that keeps changing shape.*'\n\n'*The question is: who has the right to rule -- and by what authority?*'\n\nThe portraits glow. Each leads to a different century, a different answer.",
