      "text": "While kings and parliaments fight over political authority, another revolution is happening in the laboratories and observatories.\n\nFrancis Bacon publishes *Novum Organum* (1620): '*Nature, to be commanded, must be obeyed.*' His *inductive method* -- start with observations, test through experiment, then draw conclusions -- overturns 1,500 years of arguing from authority. Truth is not found in old books. Truth is found by *looking*.\n\nThe Royal Society is founded in 1660. Its motto: *Nullius in verba* -- 'Take nobody's word for it.' The oldest continuously operating scientific society in the world.\n\nAnd then Isaac Newton. The *Principia Mathematica* (1687) -- possibly the most important book in the history of science. Three laws of motion. Universal gravitation. The same force that makes an apple fall holds the moon in orbit.\n\nAlex sees the connection: the Scientific Revolution and the political revolution are the same revolution, fought on different fronts. In both, the question is: *who has the authority to tell you what is true?* A king? A church? An ancient philosopher? Or the evidence of your own eyes, tested by reason and experiment?",
