      "text": "Prague, 1618. Protestant nobles throw three Catholic officials out of a castle window. They fall seventy feet. (They survive -- Catholics say angels caught them; Protestants say they landed in a dung heap.)\n\nThis is the *Defenestration of Prague*, and it triggers the Thirty Years' War -- the deadliest conflict in European history before the twentieth century.\n\nIt begins as a religious war: Protestants vs. Catholics in the Holy Roman Empire. But it becomes something else. Catholic France, under Cardinal Richelieu, funds *Protestant* armies against Catholic Austria. Why? *Raison d'etat* -- reason of state. National interest now matters more than religious solidarity.\n\nGermany is destroyed. Twenty-five to thirty-three percent of the population dies. The Sack of Magdeburg (1631) kills 20,000 civilians. Schiller writes: '*In less than twelve hours, this fine and populous city was reduced to ashes.*'\n\nWhen it ends, the combatants are so exhausted that they try something new. Instead of a victor's peace, they negotiate a *balanced* peace -- one that includes everyone, assigns no blame, and establishes rules for coexistence.",
