      "title": "The Birth Certificate of the Modern World",
      "text": "The Peace of Westphalia (1648). Two treaties signed simultaneously in Osnabruck and Munster. Historians call it the '*birth certificate of the modern state system.*'\n\nThree principles:\n\n*State sovereignty*: each ruler has supreme authority within their own territory. No emperor, no pope can override them.\n\n*Equality of sovereign states*: all recognized states are legally equal, regardless of size. The Netherlands counts as much as France.\n\n*Non-interference*: no state may meddle in the internal affairs of another.\n\nAlex realizes: these three principles are the *operating system* of the modern world. The United Nations is built on them. International law assumes them. Every passport, every border, every embassy exists because of what was decided in 1648.\n\nBut there is a trade-off. Sovereignty means no external authority can stop a ruler from oppressing their own people. The *balance of power* -- the idea that no single nation should dominate -- works only as long as nations balance each other. When the balance breaks...\n\nHugo Grotius, writing before Westphalia, had already asked: are there rules that bind *all* nations, even in war? '*Natural law governs nations as it governs individuals.*'",
