      "text": "Descartes: '*Cogito, ergo sum*' -- I think, therefore I am. Doubt everything except the mind that doubts. Newton: mathematics describes the universe. Locke: the mind at birth is a *tabula rasa* -- a blank slate written on by experience.\n\nThese three ideas combine into something explosive: if the universe runs on discoverable laws, and if human reason can discover them, then *everything* can be improved by applying reason -- government, law, education, religion, economics, medicine.\n\nJohn Locke writes the *Second Treatise of Government* (1689): in the state of nature, all people are free and equal. They have *natural rights* -- life, liberty, and property. Government exists to protect these rights. If it fails, the people may replace it.\n\nThis is the *social contract*: government by consent. Not divine right. Not tradition. Not force. *Agreement*.\n\nAlex watches the idea ripple outward: to Jefferson ('*life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness*'), to the French Declaration of the Rights of Man, to every democratic constitution written since.",
